04985nam a22006135i 9780226093284DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260932847 a10.7208/97802260932842doi  a(DE-B1597)524206  a(OCoLC)883632085  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHD7293.Z9bH6775 2014 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a333.33/80973223  aQT 3602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/142113:00aHousing and Mortgage Markets in Historical Perspective /cEugene N. White, Kenneth Snowden, Price V. Fishback. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (496 p.) :b65 line drawings, 50 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Conference Report00tFrontmatter -- tRelation of the Directors to the Work and Publications of the National Bureau of Economic Research -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Historiography of Early NBER Housing and Mortgage Research -- t2. The Interwar Housing Cycle in the Light of 2001-2012: A Comparative Historical Perspective -- t3. Consumption and Investment Booms in the 1920s and Their Collapse in 1930 -- t4. Lessons from the Great American Real Estate Boom and Bust of the 1920s -- t5. The 1920s American Real Estate Boom and the Downturn of the Great Depression: Evidence from City Cross- Sections -- t6. New Multicity Estimates of the Changes in Home Values, 1920-1940 -- t7. The Prolonged Resolution of Troubled Real Estate Lenders during the 1930s -- t8. Dutch Securities for American Land Speculation in the Late Eighteenth Century -- t9. Lending to Lemons: Landschaft Credit in Eighteenth- Century Prussia -- t10. The Twentieth- Century Increase in US Home Ownership: Facts and Hypotheses -- t11. Did Housing Policies Cause the Postwar Boom in Home Ownership? -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe central role of the housing market in the recent recession raised a series of questions about similar episodes throughout economic history. Were the underlying causes of housing and mortgage crises the same in earlier episodes? Has the onset and spread of crises changed over time? How have previous policy interventions either damaged or improved long-run market performance and stability? This volume begins to answer these questions, providing a much-needed context for understanding recent events by examining how historical housing and mortgage markets worked-and how they sometimes failed. Renowned economic historians Eugene N. White, Kenneth Snowden, and Price Fishback survey the foundational research on housing crises, comparing that of the 1930s to that of the early 2000s in order to authoritatively identify what contributed to each crisis. Later chapters explore notable historical experiences with mortgage securitization and the role that federal policy played in the surge in home ownership between 1940 and 1960. By providing a broad historical overview of housing and mortgage markets, the volume offers valuable new insights to inform future policy debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHousing policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aHousingxFinancexHistory. 0aHousingxPriceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMortgage loanszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aResidential real estatezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aFishback, Price V., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSnowden, Kenneth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWhite, Eugene N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-20